WEBVTT

00:02.018 --> 00:09.690
I want to begin with a hypothetical situation for related hypothetical scenarios.

00:09.750 --> 00:15.719
And what I'd like you to do is think how you would approach these, but just kind of keep it to yourself.

00:15.739 --> 00:17.001
Don't say it out loud, what you would do.

00:17.622 --> 00:20.266
But just in your own mind, sort of answer the questions.

00:21.128 --> 00:27.858
So here we go, scenario number one, you're the city manager for Grand Rapids.

00:28.098 --> 00:33.004
Now Grand Rapids is the kind of city where it's not the mayor who runs the city, it's the city manager who runs the city.

00:33.445 --> 00:41.495
So you're responsible for the whole city, lots of people report to you, lots of responsibilities, big budget, lots of stress and things that go with that.

00:42.156 --> 00:50.466
Imagine that you're the city manager for Grand Rapids and that one day you're out sort of downtown walking on the street.

00:50.486 --> 00:53.810
Now you're busy, you got a lot going on, you have a lot you're responsible for.

00:54.786 --> 01:00.873
And somebody recognizes you walking downtown Grand Rapids, total stranger, you don't know them, never seen them before.

01:02.194 --> 01:04.897
They stop you and say, hey, aren't you the city manager?

01:05.478 --> 01:08.782
I've got a great idea that's gonna make this city a lot better.

01:09.282 --> 01:12.185
Can I have an appointment to come see you and pitch you my idea?

01:13.427 --> 01:15.749
Now here's the question I just want you to answer silently in your own head.

01:16.850 --> 01:19.233
Would you make time in your schedule for that person?

01:22.397 --> 01:23.698
All right, second scenario.

01:24.610 --> 01:25.752
You're still the city manager.

01:26.613 --> 01:28.716
You're still walking the street downtown.

01:28.757 --> 01:32.763
And the person who comes up to you this time is not a stranger.

01:33.584 --> 01:36.088
You see them and you recognize them immediately.

01:36.128 --> 01:39.373
They are your adult daughter's best friend.

01:41.216 --> 01:43.540
They've been friends with your daughter for a long, long time.

01:43.580 --> 01:45.363
You've known them most of your life.

01:46.144 --> 01:52.594
This person says to you, hey, I've been thinking, I've got a great idea that's gonna make this city better.

01:52.834 --> 01:57.661
Could I have some of your time to be able to sit down with you and tell you my idea?

02:00.485 --> 02:05.652
Are you more likely to give that person time than the total stranger in scenario one?

02:05.773 --> 02:07.435
All right, you're just answering these questions in your head.

02:09.838 --> 02:11.721
Third scenario, you're still the city manager.

02:12.763 --> 02:15.226
You're still walking down Monroe or wherever you are downtown.

02:16.508 --> 02:20.754
This time the person that comes up to you is actually your son-in-law.

02:22.114 --> 02:26.981
He's married to that adult daughter and he's a very good kind son-in-law.

02:27.582 --> 02:30.046
He takes really good care of your daughter.

02:31.248 --> 02:35.975
And he walks up and he's like, hey dad, it's just funny that I run into you.

02:36.095 --> 02:40.682
You know, I've been thinking about an idea that would be really great for the city.

02:42.044 --> 02:45.469
Could I make some time in your schedule to come see you and tell you my idea?

02:47.993 --> 02:51.538
Are you more likely to give him a slot in your schedule?

02:52.674 --> 02:58.784
then you were the total stranger that came up to you on the city streets.

02:58.804 --> 03:00.226
All right, fourth and final scenario.

03:01.187 --> 03:02.089
You're still the city manager.

03:03.110 --> 03:03.892
You're still downtown.

03:04.873 --> 03:07.578
The person coming up to you is still your son-in-law this time.

03:09.440 --> 03:18.034
But this time when he approaches you, he says, dad, I know you've been stressing out and thinking a lot about revenue for the city.

03:19.586 --> 03:25.332
As I've been thinking about it with you, I've got a great idea how we could raise more revenues in the city.

03:26.954 --> 03:33.781
Would you mind if I made an appointment to come see you so we could talk about it?

03:33.801 --> 03:41.529
Are you more willing to give him the time in that situation on your busy schedule?

03:41.549 --> 03:43.891
All right, thank you for not answering any of those questions out loud.

03:45.973 --> 03:46.834
This morning,

03:48.706 --> 03:50.748
We're talking about prayer.

03:52.630 --> 04:03.902
Now in the book of 1 John, the book is written in part to help us understand the benefits of receiving Jesus in our lives.

04:06.185 --> 04:18.418
One of the greatest benefits is that because of Jesus, we have access to the Father, where we can come and say to Him, ask Him anything that we want.

04:20.066 --> 04:24.713
And so this morning we want to think together about this privilege of prayer.

04:25.914 --> 04:33.545
We want to think together about the confidence that we as children of God should have when we come to God in prayer.

04:34.367 --> 04:40.555
And then I want to say a word about the contents of what we should be praying about.

04:40.575 --> 04:47.986
So let me invite you to take a Bible and turn to the book of 1 John chapter 5, 1 John 5.

04:48.354 --> 04:54.743
If you didn't bring a Bible with you, or maybe you're not that familiar with the Bible, there's a Bible in the rack in front of you.

04:55.564 --> 05:02.333
If you take one of those Bibles and open it up to page 988, you'll be in 1 John 5.

05:03.795 --> 05:10.665
Page 988, 1 John is this little epistle, it's a little letter written by the Apostle John.

05:11.205 --> 05:14.009
He wrote a gospel called the Gospel of John.

05:14.450 --> 05:17.394
He wrote three epistles called 1st, 2nd, and 3rd John.

05:17.474 --> 05:21.059
And he wrote the final book in the Bible called the Book of Revelation.

05:21.760 --> 05:25.486
We're in the longest letter that he wrote, which is first John.

05:26.247 --> 05:30.172
We're in chapter five and I'm gonna read for us verses 13 to 17.

05:31.134 --> 05:35.220
So page 988, verses 13 to 17.

05:37.863 --> 05:45.234
The Holy Spirit says, through the Apostle John, I write these things to you who believe in the name of the Son of God,

05:45.762 --> 05:48.505
so that you may know that you have eternal life.

05:49.906 --> 05:58.514
This is the confidence we have in approaching God, that if we ask anything according to His will, He hears us.

05:59.515 --> 06:05.681
And if we know that He hears us, whatever we ask, we know that we have what we asked of Him.

06:05.721 --> 06:15.730
If you see any brother or sister commit a sin that does not lead to death, you should pray and God will give them life.

06:16.450 --> 06:19.374
I refer to those whose sin does not lead to death.

06:20.134 --> 06:21.816
There is sin that leads to death.

06:22.317 --> 06:23.939
I'm not saying you should pray about that.

06:25.581 --> 06:30.487
All wrong doing is sin, and there is sin that does not lead to death.

06:31.849 --> 06:39.578
We begin our passage this morning in the first section, thinking about the confidence God wants us to have in prayer.

06:40.699 --> 06:46.226
In verse 13, John reaffirms what he said at the beginning

06:46.498 --> 07:02.182
of this epistle, which is the great news is that we have received from God the gift that goes beyond possible imagination, the greatest gift of all time, not a thing, but a person.

07:03.203 --> 07:05.406
We have received Jesus.

07:06.067 --> 07:10.274
That's what 1 John is about, that God has given us the word of life.

07:11.836 --> 07:13.138
Now in verse 13,

07:13.314 --> 07:16.899
It may seem like the thing God has given us is eternal life.

07:17.520 --> 07:18.261
It does say that.

07:18.721 --> 07:31.479
You may know that you have eternal life, but if you look up just a couple of verses above it in verse 11, this is the testimony God has given us eternal life and this life is where?

07:32.941 --> 07:37.827
In his son, to have eternal life, you receive the son.

07:37.867 --> 07:38.548
It's a person.

07:38.889 --> 07:39.730
It's not a thing.

07:40.130 --> 07:46.117
And sometimes we get a little distracted because we think about the fact that, oh yes, I have received eternal life.

07:46.397 --> 07:48.700
I've been given access to heaven.

07:49.340 --> 07:58.410
But in reality, John is wanting to remind us all the stuff we get is because we receive a person, Jesus.

07:58.831 --> 08:05.138
That when you buy faith except Jesus, when you establish a relationship with Jesus, when you get connected

08:05.314 --> 08:16.752
to Jesus, John says what happens is as you're receiving from God Jesus and in our passage, that should give you confidence in prayer.

08:19.716 --> 08:23.422
See verse 14, this is the confidence we have in approaching God.

08:23.743 --> 08:28.971
This is the confidence that we've received Jesus, that we have a relationship with Jesus.

08:30.333 --> 08:33.618
The reason we went through those four hypothetical scenarios

08:34.210 --> 08:35.512
It's in the first scenario.

08:36.614 --> 08:37.536
You're the city manager.

08:37.857 --> 08:38.999
It's a total stranger.

08:39.700 --> 08:42.666
My guess, if you're like me, you've got a busy schedule.

08:42.706 --> 08:46.112
A total stranger walks up to you on the street, wants some time in your schedule.

08:46.452 --> 08:48.897
You're probably going to be like, maybe not.

08:50.580 --> 08:54.587
But in the second scenario, it's not a total stranger.

08:56.010 --> 08:58.194
It's your adult daughter's best friend.

08:59.650 --> 09:07.962
The reason I use that analogy is in John 15, Jesus says, when we receive Him, we become friends of Jesus.

09:09.164 --> 09:09.865
Isn't that amazing?

09:10.706 --> 09:12.609
If you're here today and you're like, I don't have any friends.

09:12.749 --> 09:14.111
If you know Jesus, you have a friend.

09:16.234 --> 09:17.616
Not just a Lord, but a friend.

09:19.439 --> 09:21.602
He's like, I call you my friends.

09:23.044 --> 09:25.488
I share with you what's going on in my life.

09:26.429 --> 09:27.631
That's what makes us friends.

09:28.533 --> 09:29.554
Well, John is saying,

09:29.826 --> 09:37.255
When you are the friend of the Son of God and you show up to talk to God, guess what?

09:38.357 --> 09:40.079
He's going to make time to talk to you.

09:40.099 --> 09:45.326
In the third scenario, it was your son-in-law.

09:46.227 --> 09:52.655
Now we use that analogy because when you and I receive Jesus, we become one with him.

09:53.796 --> 09:58.162
Marriage is one really good example of what that looks like.

09:58.914 --> 10:02.579
Two individuals become one in marriage.

10:03.300 --> 10:07.405
God says, that's just a symbol of what actually happens when you receive Jesus.

10:07.725 --> 10:14.214
When you receive Jesus, you become as intimately connected to Jesus as humanly possible.

10:14.935 --> 10:16.356
You are one with Him.

10:17.258 --> 10:23.225
So in our analogy, as the city manager, it's the son-in-law, a good son-in-law.

10:23.426 --> 10:24.527
That's why we hadn't felt that way.

10:25.248 --> 10:26.930
Who treats the daughter really well.

10:27.714 --> 10:29.417
Are you going to give that person time?

10:30.359 --> 10:31.141
Well, yes, of course.

10:32.483 --> 10:36.311
John's saying, this is the confidence we have in approaching the Father.

10:37.253 --> 10:39.617
We are one with the Son.

10:39.677 --> 10:43.825
We are in the closest possible relationship to Jesus.

10:44.186 --> 10:50.258
When we come to God and we're like, I'd like some time, the answer is always going to be yes.

10:55.490 --> 11:03.864
Now the rest of verse 14 says that if we ask anything according to his will, he hears us.

11:03.884 --> 11:06.228
That was the reason for the fourth scenario.

11:07.650 --> 11:10.535
In the fourth scenario, it's not just the son-in-law that comes up.

11:11.817 --> 11:17.907
The son-in-law says to the city manager, I know you're concerned about raising revenues in the city.

11:17.927 --> 11:22.354
I want to talk to you about the thing you're wanting to talk about.

11:23.778 --> 11:37.871
That's what John's saying is that when we come to God, wanting to talk about the things he wants to talk about, we can have absolute confidence that he's gonna listen to what we have to say.

11:39.853 --> 11:42.396
Now, what are the things God wants to talk about?

11:43.197 --> 11:44.598
We're gonna get to that in just a second.

11:45.579 --> 11:48.902
But before we do, we have to address the elephant in the room.

11:50.924 --> 11:53.106
The elephant in the room is verse 15.

11:54.818 --> 12:05.131
And if we know that he hears us, whatever we ask, we know that we have what we asked of him.

12:07.434 --> 12:19.388
The elephant in the room is that every single one of us have asked for things from God and not gotten them.

12:19.408 --> 12:19.649
Right?

12:21.631 --> 12:23.954
We've asked for things with good motives.

12:25.090 --> 12:28.715
We've asked for things with prayer, with fasting.

12:29.155 --> 12:30.837
We've begged God for things.

12:31.238 --> 12:34.562
We found verses that said it seems like you want to do this.

12:35.724 --> 12:39.528
We've really, really asked God in every possible way.

12:39.789 --> 12:42.312
We asked other people to pray for us.

12:42.332 --> 12:49.161
We did everything we can imagine to approach God and we didn't get what we asked for.

12:51.423 --> 12:53.426
So what in the world is verse 15 talking about?

12:55.714 --> 13:01.302
Well, if you can't tell, this has been a personal struggle for me, and not just a theoretical one.

13:03.225 --> 13:07.651
There's been untold frustration of God, I'm doing the stuff.

13:09.153 --> 13:10.776
I'm trying everything here.

13:11.437 --> 13:13.500
I'm pretty sure you want to do this.

13:14.281 --> 13:20.470
This feels like this would be the right thing to do, but you're not doing it.

13:21.952 --> 13:23.314
And so in the personal struggle,

13:24.834 --> 13:25.815
in God's kindness.

13:27.157 --> 13:32.623
He's explained to me something that hopefully will be helpful for you about this idea.

13:33.103 --> 13:36.987
It's just that he used in my life a different passage than verse 15.

13:37.047 --> 13:38.369
It's related but different.

13:38.929 --> 13:46.738
So I'd like to use that passage to try to explain what it is that God's at least taught me about this, that hopefully will be helpful for you.

13:47.499 --> 13:50.422
It comes out of Matthew chapter seven, verses seven and eight.

13:51.383 --> 13:52.564
This is Jesus speaking.

13:53.425 --> 13:54.066
Ask,

13:54.562 --> 13:55.703
and it will be given you.

13:56.745 --> 13:58.687
Seek and you will find.

13:59.368 --> 14:01.891
Knock and the door will be open to you.

14:02.532 --> 14:09.761
For everyone who asks, receives, the one who seeks, finds, and to the one who knocks, the door will be opened.

14:10.602 --> 14:15.709
Now that verse seems to be saying the same thing as verse 15, which is, yeah, just go ahead and ask and you're gonna get it.

14:16.750 --> 14:19.874
There's not a lot of like exception clauses in this verse.

14:21.055 --> 14:23.058
Ask and it will be given to you.

14:23.202 --> 14:25.746
Everyone who asks receives.

14:27.949 --> 14:30.333
It can be lonely to feel like, well, I'm asking and not receiving.

14:30.373 --> 14:31.295
Am I not anybody?

14:31.315 --> 14:33.258
Do I not qualify?

14:34.540 --> 14:40.809
Well, in working through this God in his kindness, I will say the asking one was not that helpful for me.

14:40.869 --> 14:43.854
The seeking one was not that helpful.

14:44.295 --> 14:48.762
The knocking one was the one the Lord was like, let me explain it using that one.

14:50.264 --> 14:51.506
And this was my understanding.

14:53.122 --> 14:56.325
When you knock, that's a metaphor for prayer.

14:58.407 --> 15:02.091
God said to me, have I ever not opened the door?

15:03.913 --> 15:06.635
Do you imagine prayer is knocking on the door of heaven?

15:07.336 --> 15:10.980
Have I ever heard a voice from the other side saying, you know, not today?

15:11.020 --> 15:16.365
And the answer if I'm honest is no, never once.

15:17.086 --> 15:21.330
Even when I'm mired in all sorts of sin, or he always opens the door.

15:23.650 --> 15:30.180
And as the Lord sort of worked me through this, He's like, now what happens when a door opens?

15:30.200 --> 15:34.627
Well, somebody either comes in or somebody comes out.

15:34.847 --> 15:35.868
That's what doors are for.

15:37.571 --> 15:50.270
And as I work through the imagery with the Lord and praying through it, the idea is listen, every single time you and I pray, we're knocking on the door of heaven.

15:50.290 --> 15:52.754
And this verse and verse 15,

15:53.218 --> 15:57.142
tell us every single time the door opens.

15:59.564 --> 16:01.005
And who's on the other side of that door?

16:02.547 --> 16:02.867
Jesus.

16:05.390 --> 16:08.352
And in my mind's eye, God says, and look in his hands.

16:11.595 --> 16:13.197
He's not coming empty-handed.

16:15.599 --> 16:18.302
Now, it may not be the gift you asked for.

16:19.243 --> 16:20.644
Maybe you're asking for healing.

16:20.684 --> 16:22.706
He may not be holding healing in his hands.

16:24.258 --> 16:28.123
It might be comfort for the fact that he's not healing you.

16:29.505 --> 16:34.572
It might be a word of encouragement from a friend that comes at just the right time.

16:35.233 --> 16:38.378
It might be a scripture passage that you'd never seen before.

16:40.120 --> 16:43.965
It might be a good night's sleep when you haven't had one for a while.

16:45.788 --> 16:50.194
It might be an explanation as to why God is choosing not to heal you.

16:51.234 --> 16:57.140
But the truth is, Jesus never comes through that door empty-handed.

16:58.202 --> 16:59.643
That's what this verse means.

17:00.784 --> 17:05.029
When you ask, you will always receive something.

17:06.691 --> 17:09.654
It may not be the thing you want it, but it's something.

17:10.495 --> 17:20.786
When you seek, you will always find something because when you knock every single

17:20.898 --> 17:23.261
time the door opens.

17:24.903 --> 17:36.336
And every single time Jesus walks into the situation and He never comes empty-handed.

17:36.356 --> 17:41.062
That's what verse 15 is saying in our passage.

17:41.082 --> 17:42.563
God's not a vending machine.

17:43.965 --> 17:44.846
He's not a genie.

17:46.588 --> 17:48.370
He's not an automated assistant.

17:49.378 --> 17:56.167
You don't sort of plug in the right words or put in enough money or do certain things and get an outcome.

17:58.130 --> 18:00.594
He's the father, we're the children.

18:01.515 --> 18:03.998
It's his will, not ours.

18:05.500 --> 18:18.258
But the promise of verse 15, the confidence that you and I can have, because of our relationship with Jesus, he will always, always, always open the door.

18:19.170 --> 18:27.282
And he will always, always, always bring something with him when he comes into the situation.

18:28.464 --> 18:32.170
Verse 15 is not written to make excuses for God.

18:32.751 --> 18:36.677
The purpose of verse 15 is not to try to say, well, he doesn't really do.

18:36.697 --> 18:38.239
He sometimes does what he wants.

18:38.259 --> 18:45.450
Verse 15 is trying to remind us every time you pray, every time, every time.

18:47.253 --> 18:48.114
He opens the door.

18:48.898 --> 18:53.803
and he brings something with him.

18:53.823 --> 18:56.145
When we ask according to his will.

18:57.546 --> 19:00.589
Now that raises the question that we kind of put on hold just a few minutes ago.

19:01.270 --> 19:03.212
How do we know what we're supposed to pray?

19:03.252 --> 19:06.235
The city manager obviously needs to raise revenues for the city.

19:06.655 --> 19:06.935
Great.

19:07.776 --> 19:09.878
What does God want us to talk to him about?

19:10.699 --> 19:12.401
Well, that's verses 16 and 17.

19:13.322 --> 19:17.906
This is not the only thing God wants us to talk to him about, but it's an example.

19:18.978 --> 19:23.183
Basically, if you're going to see the city manager, like I wonder what the city manager is worried about.

19:23.223 --> 19:24.644
Is he worried about snow removal?

19:24.704 --> 19:26.086
Is she worried about raising revenue?

19:26.386 --> 19:27.808
Is she worried about the police force?

19:27.828 --> 19:29.310
What are the things she's worried about?

19:29.690 --> 19:44.146
Verses 16 and 17 is telling us, if you're gonna knock on the door of heaven, you can ask for lots of stuff, but one of the things you and I should ask for, the contents of our prayer is found in Verses 16 and 17.

19:45.858 --> 19:53.590
If you see any brother or sister commit a sin, you should pray and God will give them life.

19:55.133 --> 20:06.351
One of the things God wants us to talk to him about, one of the things that's on his heart in mind is other believers who are struggling with sin.

20:07.533 --> 20:10.738
He wants us to come and talk to him about that.

20:11.938 --> 20:17.227
Stop in the city manager on the street to say, I got a plan for revenue because I know you're concerned about revenue.

20:17.287 --> 20:20.592
Probably going to get you a time slot.

20:20.612 --> 20:30.689
Talking to God about a brother or sister who's in sin is always going to get his attention because he's interested in that.

20:32.031 --> 20:38.962
Now, the only trick is John has phrased what he said here in terms that confuse us.

20:39.362 --> 20:44.968
because he talks about a sin that leads to death and sin that doesn't lead to death.

20:45.749 --> 20:48.191
And that has created a lot of confusion.

20:50.234 --> 20:55.820
Some people think that what John is doing is dividing sins up into two groups.

20:56.761 --> 20:58.022
The Roman Catholics use this.

20:58.042 --> 21:05.650
They'll talk about mortal sins, which is death sins and venial sins, which is not death sins.

21:06.114 --> 21:14.785
Some people talk about the difference between intentional sin and unintentional sin, sinning with a hard heart versus sinning unintentionally.

21:16.126 --> 21:24.396
I don't think that's what John is talking about here because all sin leads to death, not just certain kinds of sins.

21:25.317 --> 21:32.226
Yes, in God's kingdom, some sins are worse than others or have different consequences than others, but the wages of all sin is death.

21:32.887 --> 21:35.570
I don't think John is talking about just certain kinds of sin.

21:36.994 --> 21:57.474
Another option is some people think that John is talking about blasphemy of the Holy Spirit, which is the refusal to believe that Jesus is the Messiah, or apostasy, the sort of walking away rejecting of Jesus, so that what John is talking about here is not actual sins you commit, but the idea that we're rejecting Jesus.

21:59.316 --> 22:05.362
I don't think that's what he's talking about either, because in verse 16, he says, if you see any what?

22:06.882 --> 22:10.728
Brother or sister, we're talking about Christians here.

22:11.209 --> 22:18.401
We're not talking about people who committed blasphemy against the Holy Spirit or people who have walked away from the Lord in an apostate sort of way.

22:20.024 --> 22:26.795
So what is John talking about when he talks about sins that lead to death and sins that don't lead to death?

22:26.815 --> 22:28.217
I think it's a more basic answer.

22:29.940 --> 22:33.426
In rare situations, when Christians sin,

22:34.594 --> 22:37.116
The immediate result can be physical death.

22:39.839 --> 22:44.343
In Acts chapter five, when Ananias and Sephira lied to the Holy Spirit, they die immediately.

22:45.584 --> 22:48.107
Peter doesn't pray for them.

22:48.127 --> 22:51.550
When Uza touches the ark in the Old Testament, he dies immediately.

22:53.132 --> 22:55.434
David and nobody else prays for him because he's died.

22:55.474 --> 22:58.036
John's like, this does occasionally happen.

22:58.737 --> 23:03.922
It does occasionally happen that God institute the wages of sin immediately and death happens.

23:04.354 --> 23:07.437
John's saying, we're just not talking about those rarer cases.

23:08.879 --> 23:17.148
What we are talking about is the majority of cases where when sin happens, there is not immediate physical death.

23:18.089 --> 23:23.816
And John says, that's when you and I are supposed to step in and start praying.

23:23.836 --> 23:28.441
Let me give you some examples from the Bible as to what this looks like.

23:28.461 --> 23:29.682
Genesis chapter 20.

23:31.234 --> 23:38.645
Abraham is not told the truth about his wife, Sarah, as a result, a bimilek may end up the dangerous he could sleep with her.

23:38.705 --> 23:41.710
There could be a sexual immorality that happens as a result of this.

23:41.730 --> 23:49.442
So God appears to a bimilek in a dream and says to him, now return Abraham's wife for he's a prophet and he will pray for you and you will live.

23:50.163 --> 23:55.892
But if you do not return her, you may be sure that you and all who belong to you will die.

23:57.093 --> 24:00.178
Then Abraham prayed to God and God healed the bimilek

24:00.386 --> 24:09.897
His wife and his female slaves so they could have children again, for the Lord had kept all the women in a bimilex household from conceiving because of Abraham's wife, Sarah.

24:10.497 --> 24:19.928
Somehow because of this sin, I don't know that any of these women knew it, but in that moment, all of these women were under the judgment of God and God's like, you better ask Abraham and he'll pray for you.

24:20.368 --> 24:26.935
And Abraham does 1 John 5, which is he prays and God hears it and he removes the sin.

24:28.437 --> 24:29.298
Numbers 14.

24:29.890 --> 24:32.754
The nation of Israel has refused to go into the promised land.

24:32.774 --> 24:34.337
God is going to destroy them all.

24:35.438 --> 24:43.390
Moses prays, in accordance with your great love, forgive the sin of these people, just as you have pardoned them from the time they left Egypt until now.

24:43.791 --> 24:47.176
The Lord replied, I have forgiven them as you've asked.

24:48.277 --> 24:54.426
Now if you compare that with Numbers 25, where they commit sexual immorality with the Moabites, there's no prayer that's offered there.

24:54.446 --> 24:56.369
They just immediately die for doing that.

24:57.411 --> 24:59.634
That's 1 John saying, those sins led to death.

25:00.002 --> 25:06.708
But in Numbers 14, those sins did not lead to death, and so Moses' job is prayed for these people so that they won't die.

25:08.610 --> 25:16.498
Job chapter one, when a period of feasting had run its course, Job would make arrangements for them, his children, to be purified.

25:16.998 --> 25:24.525
Early in the morning, he would sacrifice a burnt offering for each of them thinking, perhaps my children have sinned and cursed God in their hearts.

25:25.026 --> 25:26.987
This was Job's regular custom.

25:27.808 --> 25:29.810
And then also at the end of Job,

25:30.754 --> 25:35.000
after the Job's friends have sort of caused been a stumbling block to Job.

25:35.300 --> 25:42.249
God says, so now take seven bowls and seven rams and go to my servant Job and sacrifice a burnt offering for yourselves.

25:42.269 --> 25:48.918
My servant Job will pray for you and I will accept his prayer and not deal with you according to your folly.

25:49.960 --> 26:00.754
These are all examples of people doing 1 John 5 verses 16 and 17, praying for those who have been tripped up by sin where the sin has not resulted in immediate death.

26:03.010 --> 26:09.118
The most famous example of this is Jesus on the cross, praying Father, forgive them.

26:10.179 --> 26:13.263
They don't know what they're doing.

26:13.283 --> 26:16.347
This is what God is wanting to hear from us.

26:16.367 --> 26:23.295
It's not the only thing he wants to hear from us, but if you're wondering, what is the thing that God wants me to come talk about?

26:23.556 --> 26:31.986
One of the things you can be absolutely certain is on his mind is that God loves being merciful.

26:33.122 --> 26:33.783
He loves it.

26:34.945 --> 26:36.727
He delights in being merciful.

26:37.047 --> 26:37.789
I don't know about you.

26:37.849 --> 26:41.634
Maybe you woke up this morning like, man, I can't wait to have breakfast.

26:41.654 --> 26:42.575
I can't wait to have lunch.

26:42.715 --> 26:43.997
I can't wait to watch the Super Bowl.

26:44.258 --> 26:48.343
Maybe there's all sorts of things that you and I delight in when God wakes up in the morning.

26:49.064 --> 26:49.765
He doesn't wake up.

26:49.965 --> 26:50.626
He's always awake.

26:51.147 --> 26:53.450
But metaphorically, guess what he wants to do?

26:55.012 --> 26:56.114
He wants to be merciful.

26:57.570 --> 27:03.576
Like if you've ever had a day where you've been super excited, man, I cannot wait to get downstairs to play video games.

27:03.596 --> 27:05.779
I cannot wait to open Christmas presents.

27:05.799 --> 27:10.744
I cannot, whatever it is that in your heart, you're like, yes, that's the thing I most wanted to.

27:11.044 --> 27:15.770
I cannot wait for a beautiful summer day at Lake Michigan when it's 80 degrees outside.

27:16.070 --> 27:21.295
Whatever it is that you can't wait for, that's how God feels about being merciful.

27:21.716 --> 27:23.698
That's what he loves to do.

27:25.922 --> 27:30.868
And when you and I knock on the door and we're like, hey, can we talk about my wife?

27:30.968 --> 27:32.169
Can we talk about my husband?

27:32.189 --> 27:33.371
Can we talk about my kids?

27:33.651 --> 27:34.973
Can we talk about my siblings?

27:35.013 --> 27:36.434
Can we talk about my coworkers?

27:36.655 --> 27:38.317
Can we talk about my friends at school?

27:39.818 --> 27:41.741
I would like you to be merciful to them.

27:41.801 --> 27:43.883
Guess what?

27:43.903 --> 27:46.046
He's ecstatic to hear you say that.

27:47.547 --> 27:49.810
He wants to have that conversation with us.

27:50.850 --> 27:53.894
When we say to God, and look, Lord, please have mercy on them.

27:53.914 --> 27:55.677
Please get them out of the sin.

27:55.737 --> 27:59.502
Now, because we all have free will, he doesn't override our free will.

28:00.824 --> 28:03.127
But he delights in being merciful.

28:03.788 --> 28:06.131
He loves talking about these things.

28:08.434 --> 28:19.890
And so if you want to pray anything that's in accordance with his will, if you want to pray anything that you know he's going to want to hear, 1 John 5, 16, and 7, and he says,

28:20.482 --> 28:24.489
find somebody you know and somebody you love who's struggling with sin.

28:25.651 --> 28:26.553
Maybe it's tripping them up.

28:27.274 --> 28:28.516
Maybe they're deceived by it.

28:29.177 --> 28:31.020
Maybe it's causing destruction in their life.

28:32.463 --> 28:33.605
Ask God to set them free.

28:34.586 --> 28:35.708
Ask God to be merciful.

28:36.530 --> 28:39.234
Ask God to not treat them the way their sins deserve.

28:40.236 --> 28:45.906
You will always, always find a ready audience wanting to talk to you about those things.

